  "text": "Most important differential diagnosis is unilateral Blount's disease, a developmental disorder with progressive genu varum (5). Further differential diagnosis include dyschondrosteosis, fibrous dysplasia, Ollier's disease, neurofibromatosis or trauma [CITATION_1] . A fibrous tether at the distal aspect of femur may also cause genu valgum or genu varum, depending on the location of the tether. In contrast to FFCD these lesions are purely fibrous and show no evidence of any cartilaginous or osseous elements (6).",
